ers, Ruben J. Garcia demonstrates that when it comes to these marginal workers, the sum of the law is less than its parts, and, despite what appears to be a plethora of applicable statutes, marginal workers are frequently lacking in protection. To ameliorate the status of marginal workers, he argues for a new paradigm in worker protection, one based on human freedom and rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination in employmentxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in employmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aForeign workersxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aForeign workersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aForeign workersxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aLabor laws and legislationxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aLabor laws and legislationzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814738634.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814738634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814738634/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles